            <p>Alexa Fairchild, who stands at just over five feet tall, doesn't look particularly formidable. But many of her students and even colleagues find her intimidating. "Her mind just seems to work differently," said a former colleague, himself a world renowned mathematician. "I once brought a theorem to her that I thought she might have some ideas about how to attack. Right there in her office, in the span of forty five minutes she'd basically sketched out a full proof. I'd spent six months trying to prove it myself before I'd showed it to her!"</p>

            <p>The 33 year old physicist who recently received tenure at the illustrious Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, didn't always love math, but she did grow up obsessed with puzzles. Sitting in her office at the IAS her excitement was palpable.</p>

            <p>"I can remember being obsessed with puzzles way back in elementary school. In high school, I got C's in algebra and pre-calculus, because I spent all my time solving strange puzzles," Fairchild recalls. "I was obsessed with an old book I had by Martin Gardner. He was this mathematician who spent his time devising and tweaking puzzles for public consumption."</p>

            <p>Fairchild is such a die hard puzzle fanatic that she has a puzzle tattooed on her [body].</p>

            <p>Fairchild didn't take math seriously until she got to college, but once she did, the gloves came off. "I realized calculus and geometry and even more advanced topics like differential topology - they were all just more abstract versions of puzzles - but puzzles that all fit together in this amazingly unified way."</p>

            <p>She became interested in physics after attending a public lecture by the renowned physicist Lisa Randall. "I heard Randall lecture, on extra dimensions I think, and I was enthralled. Here was this brilliant woman - you didn't see a lot of women represented in physics at the time - using high level mathematics to investigate the deepest puzzles about our universe. I was hooked."</p>

